>>27727178

Just to echo what others have already said, the world you're building should be driven by the kind of sorry you want to write. I would go further, as my favorite kind of story to write is one where the world is the driver and the story forms around how the characters interact with it.

If you're really having a hard time figuring out the larger fits into your story, chances are that it doesn't have much bearing on it. It's not a problem if the world in your story isn't much more than a couple of rooms and a job site or two - hell, the job might only be referenced in passing. Lots of great plays have been written with a single room set, and the same goes for other literally works. If the larger world doesn't have any effect on your characters it your plot then it probably won't add much for your reader. Hell, it might become a distraction for them, if nothing else.

I could reference this in a breakdown of one of my own stories, if I folks were interested, though I'm not sure if I could endure sniffing my own farts for that long.

You said almost exactly what my experience was for that first long-form piece.
I had a few ideas on how the world differed from ours, and the broad events of the story. As I wrote, the characters and the how of the events became clear.

There's tons of exercise ideas to help a writer refine characters, but at the heart is basic conflict and resolution.
Let them be real. Let them lie, have contradictory opinions, or do things for no apparent reason.
To paraphrase someone better that me, if you just write the damned thing, and have scrap of talent, something will fall out. Nurture it. The characters aren't you, so take your hands off their strings.
The results may shock you
